My life has changed dramatically over the last year, so many beautiful things, thankful for the hard times that make these good times so much sweeter. 
I recommend viewing life as a gift given to you. With this view, you are entitled to nothing, and can be thankful for everything. View yourself as a child and love yourself as such, you are somebody worth taking care of. And also... I recommend cracking the joke. The one that enters your head at any moment. Even if it’s risky, even if it might get crickets, (and even if it might offend) — risk it, make people laugh, we all bloody need it. - Luke

A year ago I met Cindy. She was found on a construction sight, (by the beautiful @valrosecuriel) and had clearly been abused by her previous owners. She was very skittish and scared, particularly around men, including me. So I was fostering her, looking for an owner to give her all the love she deserved. But until I found someone, I wanted us to get along. Someone told me it would help her if I let her sleep in bed with me. So I did. The next morning it was like waking up to a different dog, it was as if she finally knew I wasn’t going to kill her, and she pushed her face against mine... Some people got in contact and asked to meet her... and I said no. Me and Cindy were in love, and there was nothing either of us could do about it. And it has been such a joy, taking care of her and having her excited face to come home to. Dogs nail it, don’t they? They greet you with such enthusiasm whether you’ve been gone for a month or half an hour. That’s why I write her name in my gratitude journal every day. Cindy. Love her.
Sheer socks are in, and I don’t care what anyone has to say about it.
